[3] Los Santos Province Panama
Date: Thu 15 Feb 2018
Source: Dia a Dia [in Spanish, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
https://www.diaadia.com.pa/tierra-adentro/autoridades-confirman-nuevos-casos-de-hantavirus-en-los-santos-333812


The Ministry of Health (MINSA) has confirmed 2 hantavirus cases in Los Santos province. These involve a 22-year-old youth and a 49-year-old man who are in intensive care in the Joaquin Pablo Franco Hospital in Las Tablas connected to a ventilator. The 22-year-old patient is from the El Bebedero area of Tonosi, and the 49-year-old is a resident of El Cacao in Tonosi.

Carlos Muñoz, a MINSA epidemiologist, stated that in January 2018 and in the 1st 15 days of February 2018, 5 cases of hantavirus [infections] have been reported, 4 in Tonosi and one in Guarare, and of these, 2 for hantavirus fever and 3 with cardiopulmonary syndrome, with deaths in the last week of January [2018].

Of these statistics, currently there are 3 people in the Joaquin Pablo Franco Hospital, one with [hantavirus] fever and 2 others in a delicate state connected to a ventilator.

MINSA stated that they are making house-to-house visits, especially in lower areas in the Tonosi Valley where most of the cases have occurred.

2017 ended with 23 cases, 16 with [hantavirus] fever and 7 with hantavirus cardiopulmonary syndrome.

[Byline: Zenaida Vásquez]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[There are frequent cases of infections by hantaviruses in Los Santos province. The situation in which the men acquired their infections is not mentioned. There is no indication of which hantavirus is involved in this or in previous cases in Panama. As noted in comments in previous posts, Los Santos and adjoining provinces are endemic for Choclo hantavirus. Although no data on this or the previous cases in earlier years include an indication of which hantavirus is responsible, Choclo is the only one of the 3 hantaviruses known to be endemic in Panama that causes HPS (hantavirus cardiopulmonary syndrome) or hantavirus fever. No vaccine is available for Choclo virus.

The rodent host of Choclo virus is the pygmy rice rat (_Oligoryzomys fulvescens_), a photograph of which can be accessed at http://www.medwave.cl/medios/perspectivas/Hantavirus/Actualiz/Fig2.jpg. These rodents occur in and around agricultural areas and adjacent houses and buildings. They can be persistently infected with the virus and shed it in urine, feces, and saliva.

Maps of Panama: http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/panama.jpg and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5634982,47151. - Mod.TY]
